scDistort.name: scDistort
scDistort.description: Distort a signal. This is the same as using .distort in SuperCollider.
example:
let test amp => sin 440 >> gain amp >> distort >> out 0
let t = test 1
stop t

scSoftClip.name: scSoftClip
scSoftClip.description: Distortion with a perfectly linear region from -0.5 to +0.5. This is the same as using .softclip in SuperCollider.
example:
let test amp => sin 440 >> gain amp >> scSoftClip >> out 0
let t = test 1
stop t

scRand.name: scRand
scRand.description: Generate a random number with uniform distribution when synth starts playing.
example:
let test a => sin (scRand 220 440) >> out 0
let t = test 1
stop t

scNRand.name: scNRand
scNRand.description: Generate a random number with distribution based on the sum of n random numbers when synth starts playing.

params.name: n
params.description: Number of random numbers to sum. 1 = uniform distribution, 2 = triangular, etc. Higher numbers approach gaussian

example:
let test a => sin (scNRand 220 440 4) >> out 0
let t = test 1
stop t

scTRand.name: scTRand
scTRand.description: Generate a random number with uniform distribution on each trigger.

params.name: trigger
params.description: A trigger happens when the signal changes from non-positive to positive

example:
let test a => sin (scTRand 220 440 (impulse 1)) >> out 0
let t = test 1
stop t

stepper.name: stepper
stepper.description: Triggerable steps at a given interval between minimum and maximum values.

params.name: step
params.description: The range by which each step will jump.

params.name: trigger
params.description: A trigger happens when the signal changes from non-positive to positive

example:
let stepSynth stepFreq => sin freq >> dup >> gain 0.3 >> out 0
  where
      freq = stepper 220 440 20 (impulse stepFreq)

let stSynth = stepSynth 4
stop stSynth

poll.name: poll
poll.description: Prints values from a UGen, but passes the input back out. This expensive, so only use for testing.
example:
let pollSynth freq => sin freq >> poll >> out 0
let ps = pollSynth 0.5
stop ps

coingate.name: coingate

example:

let t = test 0.5
stop t

cuspN.name: cuspN
cuspN.description: A non-interpolating sound generator based on the difference equation: x[n+1] = a - b * sqrt(abs(x[n]))
example:

let t = test 22050 1 1.9 0
stop t

gbmanN.name: gbmanN
gbmanN.description: A non-interpolating sound generator based on the difference equation: x[n+1] = 1 - y[n] + abs(x[n]); y[n+1] = x[n];
example:
let test f xi yi => gbmanN f xi yi >> out 0
let t = test 22050 1.2 2.1
stop t

env.name: env
env.description: Envelope generator. Used for amplitude envelopes, will automatically free the synth when finished.

params.name: levels
params.description: The levels that the envelope will move through

params.name: times
params.description: The times it takes for the env to move between levels. Should be 1 item less than levels

params.name: shape
params.description: Either a shape number or string. Some examples: -4, 0, 1, "linear", "squared"

example:
let test amp => white amp >> env [0,1,0] [1,1] "linear" >> out 0
test $ random 0.1 1.0

env2.name: env2
env2.description: Envelope generator. Used for amplitude envelopes, will NOT automatically free the synth when finished.

params.name: levels
params.description: The levels that the envelope will move through

params.name: times
params.description: The times it takes for the env to move between levels. Should be 1 item less than levels

params.name: shape
params.description: Either a shape number or string. Some examples: -4, 0, 1, "linear", "squared"

example:
let test f => sin (env2[f,f*2,f] [1,1] "linear" 1) >> env [0,0.3,0] [2,2] "linear" >> out 0
test $ random 440 880

perc.name: perc
perc.description: Envelope generator. Used for amplitude envelopes, will automatically free the synth when finished.

params.name: attackTime
params.description: Time for the envelope to go from 0 to the peak

params.name: peak
params.description: The highest level the envelope with reach

params.name: decayTime
params.description: Time for the envelope to go from the peak to 0

example:
let test amp => white amp >> perc 0 1 1 >> out 0
test $ random 0.1 1.0

perc2.name: perc2
perc2.description: Envelope generator. Used for amplitude envelopes, will NOT automatically free the synth when finished.

params.name: attackTime
params.description: Time for the envelope to go from 0 to the peak

params.name: peak
params.description: The highest level the envelope with reach

params.name: decayTime
params.description: Time for the envelope to go from the peak to 0

out.name: out
out.description: Send a signal to an output bus.

params.name: busNum
params.description: The bus index to send to

example:
let test bus => white 1 >> out bus
let t = test 0
stop t

auxIn.name: auxIn
auxIn.description: Reads audio from a range of audio buses.

params.name: busNum
params.description: The bus index to start reading from.

params.name: numChannels
params.description: The number of channels to read from.

example:
let simpleSynth freq => sin freq \* square (2\*tempoSeconds) * 0.25 >> out 20
let sSynth = simpleSynth 440
let fxSynth => auxIn 20 1 >> combC tempoSeconds [tempoSeconds/1, tempoSeconds/2] 10 >> out 0
let fx = Synth::after "fxSynth" [] server
stop sSynth
stop fx

pan.name: pan
pan.description: Pans a single channel input across a stereo field using equal power panning.

params.name: position
params.description: The position in the stereo field where the input will be panned. Range of -1 (left) to 1 (right).

params.name: input
params.description: The audio input to be panned.

example:
let test pos => white 1 >> pan pos >> out 0
let t = test-0.3
stop t

dup.name: dup
dup.description: Duplicates an input across a 2 index array.

params.name: input
params.description: The audio input to be expanded.

example:
let test freq => sin freq >> dup >> out 0
let t = test 440
stop t

localBuf.name: localBuf
localBuf.description: A buffer local to a synth.

params.name: frames
params.description: Size of the buffer in samples

params.name: channels
params.description: Number of channels for the buffer

example:
let test del => impulse 1 >> bufCombC (localBuf 44100 1) del 1 >> out 0
let t = test 0.1
stop t

used for tail recursive algorithms. Note that returned funciton
is not side effect free and should not be called from anywhere
else during tail recursion. In other words if
`var f = tco(function foo() { ... bar() ... })`, then `bar`
should never call `f`. It is ok though for `bar` to call `tco(foo)`
instead.

## Examples
var sum = tco(function(x, y) {
  return y > 0 ? sum(x + 1, y - 1) :
         y < 0 ? sum(x - 1, y + 1) :
         x
})
sum(20, 100000) // => 100020

Tag-closer extension for CodeMirror.

This extension adds an "autoCloseTags" option that can be set to
either true to get the default behavior, or an object to further
configure its behavior.

These are supported options:

`whenClosing` (default true)
  Whether to autoclose when the '/' of a closing tag is typed.
`whenOpening` (default true)
  Whether to autoclose the tag when the final '>' of an opening
  tag is typed.
`dontCloseTags` (default is empty tags for HTML, none for XML)
  An array of tag names that should not be autoclosed.
`indentTags` (default is block tags for HTML, none for XML)
  An array of tag names that should, when opened, cause a
  blank line to be added inside the tag, and the blank line and
  closing line to be indented.

See demos/closetag.html for a usage example.

Supported keybindings:

  Motion:
  h, j, k, l
  gj, gk
  e, E, w, W, b, B, ge, gE
  f<character>, F<character>, t<character>, T<character>
  $, ^, 0, -, +, _
  gg, G
  %
  '<character>, `<character>

  Operator:
  d, y, c
  dd, yy, cc
  g~, g~g~
  >, <, >>, <<

  Operator-Motion:
  x, X, D, Y, C, ~

  Action:
  a, i, s, A, I, S, o, O
  zz, z., z<CR>, zt, zb, z-
  J
  u, Ctrl-r
  m<character>
  r<character>

  Modes:
  ESC - leave insert mode, visual mode, and clear input state.
  Ctrl-[, Ctrl-c - same as ESC.

Registers: unamed, -, a-z, A-Z, 0-9
  (Does not respect the special case for number registers when delete
   operator is made with these commands: %, (, ),  , /, ?, n, N, {, } )
  TODO: Implement the remaining registers.
Marks: a-z, A-Z, and 0-9
  TODO: Implement the remaining special marks. They have more complex
      behavior.

Events:
 'vim-mode-change' - raised on the editor anytime the current mode changes,
                     Event object: {mode: "visual", subMode: "linewise"}

Extract the regular expression from the query and return a Regexp object.
Returns null if the query is blank.
If ignoreCase is passed in, the Regexp object will have the 'i' flag set.
If smartCase is passed in, and the query contains upper case letters,
  then ignoreCase is overridden, and the 'i' flag will not be set.
If the query contains the /i in the flag part of the regular expression,
  then both ignoreCase and smartCase are ignored, and 'i' will be passed
  through to the Regex object.

Check if pos is in the specified range, INCLUSIVE.
Range can be specified with 1 or 2 arguments.
If the first range argument is an array, treat it as an array of line
numbers. Match pos against any of the lines.
If the first range argument is a number,
  if there is only 1 range argument, check if pos has the same line
      number
  if there are 2 range arguments, then check if pos is in between the two
      range arguments.

Helper to test CodeMirror highlighting modes. It pretty prints output of the
highlighter and can check against expected styles.

Mode tests are registered by calling test.mode(testName, mode,
tokens), where mode is a mode object as returned by
CodeMirror.getMode, and tokens is an array of lines that make up
the test.

These lines are strings, in which styled stretches of code are
enclosed in brackets `[]`, and prefixed by their style. For
example, `[keyword if]`. Brackets in the code itself must be
duplicated to prevent them from being interpreted as token
boundaries. For example `a[[i]]` for `a[i]`. If a token has
multiple styles, the styles must be separated by ampersands, for
example `[tag&error </hmtl>]`.

See the test.js files in the css, markdown, gfm, and stex mode
directories for examples.

Emulation of CodeMirror's internal highlight routine for testing. Multi-line
input is supported.

classitems.description: Compare two arrays of output from highlight.

Print tokens and corresponding styles in a table. Spaces in the token are
replaced with 'interpunct' dots (·).

params.description: The expected end position of the cursor.

params.name: startPos
params.description: The position the cursor should start at, defaults to 0, 0.
